text: Between 2.5 and 3.5 % of participants were missing data at post-treatment and between 5.5 and 8 % of participants were missing data at follow-up. There was no discernable pattern of missing data and Little's test was not significant, χ 2 (483) = 477.68, p > 0.05, which indicated that data could be considered Missing Completely at Random (MCAR). Mplus uses Full Information Maximum Likelihood estimation to handle missing data, which is appropriate in cases when data are assumed to be MCAR (Enders, 2010).
